{
  "text": "The data are available from the Web [25]. Information may be downloaded in text or XML format and imported into an Excel spreadsheet, MySQL database or other applications. For advanced users, the data may be retrieved using SQL from the Web interface. A database schema is available on the SQL search page as an aid in SQL query formulation. A workflow management system is under development to automate the processing and update of proteomes. All external data are updated when a major release of NR becomes available. NR database is downloaded from NCBI. Sequences from other sequencing centers are clustered at 100% identity using cd-hit [CITATION_1] . Subsequent updates are performed monthly using the NCBI NR Month database. The unique sequences are sorted according to taxonomy using the NCBI gi_taxonomy mapping table. Only sequences that are new or changed (crc64 checksum) are submitted to a continuous update process. The release date for each source database used is given on the home page. The Arabidopsis proteome ",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "17165775"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "17165775": {
      "title": "Clustering of highly homologous sequences to reduce the size of large protein databases",
      "abstract": "Summary: We present a fast and flexible program for clustering large protein databases at different sequence identity levels. It takes less than 2 h for the all-against-all sequence comparison and clustering of the non-redundant protein database of over 560 000 sequences on a high-end PC. The output database, including only the representative sequences, can be used for more efficient and sensitive database searches. Availability: The program is available from http: //bioinformatics.burnham-inst.org/cd-hi"
    }
  }
}